## Refactor Phase Complete

**Naming Evaluation**: `validateClaimStep` still accurately describes its role as home for claim-side input guards (covers negative-amounts + more-damages-than-insured). No rename warranted.

**Refactoring Applied**: Rewrote the `more-damages-than-insured` block from a two-pass mutable `Map<string, number>` accumulator to a single-pass `Set`-of-unique-types + `filter().length` style.

**Before** (cycle 25 green-phase code):
```typescript
const damageCounts = new Map<string, number>();
for (const damage of step.incident.damages) {
  damageCounts.set(damage.itemType, (damageCounts.get(damage.itemType) ?? 0) + 1);
}
for (const [itemType, damageCount] of damageCounts) {
  const insuredCount = policyItems.filter((x) => x.type === itemType).length;
  if (damageCount > insuredCount) { throw ... }
}
```

**After**:
```typescript
const damagedTypes = new Set(step.incident.damages.map((d) => d.itemType));
for (const itemType of damagedTypes) {
  const damageCount = step.incident.damages.filter((d) => d.itemType === itemType).length;
  const insuredCount = policyItems.filter((x) => x.type === itemType).length;
  if (damageCount > insuredCount) { throw ... }
}
```

**Mass Change**: ~49 → ~39 (Δ ~-10). Eliminated: mutable `Map`, `??`-coalesce, `.set` mutation, one entire `for` loop.

**Rules applied**:
- Rule 4 (fewest elements): removed mutable accumulator and second loop
- Rule 2 (reveals intent): `filter((x) => x.type === type).length` now matches the established `componentBlockAdjustment` codebase idiom (cycle 11)
- Rule 3: deliberately did NOT extract a generic `countByType` helper — premature over two divergent sites

**Tests**: 33 passing, 1 todo — all green.

